        "text": "*[Bug 19051] New: casts from double to R_xlen_t can trigger undefined behaviour*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19051>\n\n            Bug ID: 19051\n           Summary: casts from double to R_xlen_t can trigger undefined\n                    behaviour\n           Product: R\n           Version: R-devel (trunk)\n          Hardware: Other\n                OS: Linux\n            Status: NEW\n          Severity: normal\n          Priority: P5\n         Component: Low-level\n          Assignee: <mailto:R-core@R-project.org|R-core@R-project.org>\n          Reporter: <mailto:kevinushey@gmail.com|kevinushey@gmail.com>\n\nCreated attachment 3673\n  --&gt; <https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/attachment.cgi?id=3673&amp;action=edit>\nAdd and use a helper for safe truncation \/ downcasting.\n\nThere are a number of locations where R downcasts values without checking if\nthe casted value would fit the target type. For example (using a version of R\nbuilt with ASAN + UBSAN)\n\n```\n&gt; 1[1e101]\nsubset.c:716:10: runtime error: 1e+101 is outside the range of representable\nvalues of type 'long'\nSUMMARY: UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer: undefined-behavior subset.c:716:10\nsubscript.c:803:28: runtime error: 1e+101 is outside the range of representable\nvalues of type 'long'\nSUMMARY: UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer: undefined-behavior subscript.c:803:28\nsubscript.c:843:27: runtime error: 1e+101 is outside the range of representable\nvalues of type 'long'\nSUMMARY: UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer: undefined-behavior subscript.c:843:27\nsubscript.c:861:24: runtime error: 1e+101 is outside the range of representable\nvalues of type 'long'\nSUMMARY: UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer: undefined-behavior subscript.c:861:24\nsubset.c:145:2: runtime error: 1e+101 is outside the range of representable\nvalues of type 'long'\nSUMMARY: UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer: undefined-behavior subset.c:145:2\n[1] NA\n&gt; R.version\n               _\nplatform       x86_64-pc-linux-gnu\narch           x86_64\nos             linux-gnu\nsystem         x86_64, linux-gnu\nstatus         Under development (unstable)\nmajor          4\nminor          7.0\nyear           2026\nmonth          04\nday            13\nsvn rev        89874\nlanguage       R\nversion.string R Under development (unstable) (2026-04-13 r89874)\nnickname       Unsuffered Consequences\n```\n\nThese are mostly triggered via unnaturally large index vectors (and so\nshouldn't occur in practice, at least not intentionally) but figured I would\nfile for completeness. That said, it's not clear what the correct behavior in\neach scenario is -- e.g. emit an R error, versus silent truncation.\n\n\n      216 +| # | File | Line(s) | Cast |\n      217 +|---|---|---|---|\n      218 +| 1 | `src\/main\/subset.c` | 86 | `(R_xlen_t) (di - 1)` |\n      219 +| 2 | `src\/main\/subset.c` | 716 | `(R_xlen_t) rval` |\n      220 +| 3 | `src\/main\/subscript.c` | 136 | `(R_xlen_t)(dblind - 1)` |\n      221 +| 4 | `src\/main\/subscript.c` | 254 | `(R_xlen_t)(dblind - 1)` |\n      222 +| 5 | `src\/main\/subscript.c` | 803 | `(R_xlen_t) max` |\n      223 +| 6 | `src\/main\/subscript.c` | 805 | `(R_xlen_t) max` |\n      224 +| 7 | `src\/main\/subscript.c` | 840 | `(R_xlen_t) ds` |\n      225 +| 8 | `src\/main\/subscript.c` | 843 | `(R_xlen_t) ds` |\n      226 +| 9 | `src\/main\/subscript.c` | 861 | `(R_xlen_t) ds` |\n      227 +| 10 | `src\/main\/mapply.c` | 52 | `(R_xlen_t) REAL(ans)[0]` |\n      228 +| 11 | `src\/main\/summary.c` | 1181 | `(R_xlen_t)REAL(ans)[i] - 1` |\n      229 +| 12 | `src\/main\/altclasses.c` | 53 | `(R_xlen_t) REAL0(info)[0]` |\n      230 +| 13 | `src\/main\/altclasses.c` | 55 | `(int) REAL0(info)[1]` |\n      231 +| 14 | `src\/main\/altclasses.c` | 57 | `(int) REAL0(info)[2]` |\n      232 +| 15 | `src\/main\/altclasses.c` | 60 | `(R_xlen_t) REAL0(info)[0]` |\n      233 +| 16 | `src\/main\/altclasses.c` | 61 | `(int) REAL0(info)[1]` |\n      234 +| 17 | `src\/main\/altclasses.c` | 62 | `(int) REAL0(info)[2]` |\n      235 +| 18 | `src\/main\/altclasses.c` | 359 | `(R_xlen_t) REAL0(info)[0]` |\n",
